The start symbol expands only as  

S → NT18 NT42.  

Hence the first terminal in any generated string must come from NT18.

NT18 has exactly two productions  
NT18 → 't10'  (1 token)  
NT18 → NT23 NT57  (3 tokens)

If the first production is used, the very first terminal is t10.  
If the second production is used, the expansion is

NT18 ⇒ NT23 NT57  
   ⇒ NT26 NT54 NT57  
   ⇒ (t23 | t49) t33 t31,

so the first terminal is either t23 or t49.

In every possible case, the first terminal derived from NT18 is one of  
t10, t23, or t49 – never t22.

The string we are asked to recognise begins with t22.  
Therefore it cannot be produced by NT18, and consequently cannot be produced by S.

Hence the given string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol S must derive the whole string through its only rule:

S → NT18 NT42

NT18 can either produce:
1. the single terminal t10 (NT18 → 't10'), or
2. NT23 NT57 (NT18 → NT23 NT57)

The given string begins with t40, so NT18 cannot use the first (single-terminal) option.  
Therefore NT18 must expand to NT23 NT57.

NT57 has exactly one rule:

NT57 → 't31'

Hence the token t31 must appear in the string, and immediately before it the two-token sequence generated by NT23 must appear.

But NT23 also has only one rule:

NT23 → NT26 NT54

with
NT26 → 't49' | 't23'  
NT54 → 't33'

Consequently, NT23 can generate only the two-token sequence
[t49 t33] or [t23 t33].

Therefore, somewhere in the string we would have to find the consecutive triple
[t49 t33 t31] or [t23 t33 t31].

Scanning the provided string

t40 t35 t43 t23 t27 t49 t9 t55 t55 t9 t57 t23 t6 t49 t50 t54 t31 …

reveals that the terminal t33 never appears at all.  
Since NT23 necessarily contains t33, NT18 cannot produce any substring of the given string, and thus S cannot generate the entire string.

Hence the string is not in the language defined by the grammar.

No

The start symbol is  

S → NT18 NT42  

so the first part of any sentence generated by the grammar must be derived from NT18.

The only productions for NT18 are  
• NT18 → 't10'  
• NT18 → NT23 NT57  

The second alternative leads to the terminal sequence  
 NT23 → NT26 NT54 → ('t49' | 't23') 't33'  
 NT57 → 't31'  

hence NT18 can generate only one of the following terminal strings:  
 t10  
 t49 t33 t31  
 t23 t33 t31  

All of these start with t10, t49 or t23.

The string we are asked to recognise begins with t51.  
Since NT18 can never produce a string whose first symbol is t51, the required decomposition S → NT18 NT42 is impossible, and therefore the entire string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The last token of any string generated by NT42 (the second component in the start rule S → NT18 NT42) must be one of the following:

• ‘t27’  (NT42 → 't27')  
• ‘t54’  (NT42 → 't54')  
• ‘t51’, ‘t53’ or ‘t12’  (NT42 → NT2 NT38, and NT38 → 't51' | 't53' | 't12')  
• ‘t11’  (NT42 → NT4 NT13, and NT13 → 't11')

The given string ends with ‘t50’.  
‘t50’ cannot be produced by NT38 or NT13, nor is it one of the single-token alternatives for NT42. Therefore NT42 can never generate a string whose final token is ‘t50’.

Since the start symbol S always expands to NT18 NT42, any string in the language must have a final token permitted by NT42. The provided string does not satisfy this requirement, so it cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

NT18 is the first non-terminal that contributes terminals to the start of any sentence produced by the grammar, because  

S → NT18 NT42  

NT18 has only two possibilities:  
1. NT18 → 't10' (produces a single terminal t10 as the very first symbol), or  
2. NT18 → NT23 NT57 (which necessarily produces the terminal 't31' from NT57, since NT57 → 't31').

The given string begins with t6, and it contains no occurrence of t31 at all.  
Therefore neither alternative for NT18 can match the start (or any part) of the provided string, so the string cannot be derived from the grammar.

Hence the grammar does not generate the string.

No

The start symbol S can only expand as  

S → NT18 NT42  

Therefore the derived string must start with whatever NT18 can generate.

NT18 has only two possible productions:

1. NT18 → 't10'  
   This would make the first token of the string t10.  
   The given string starts with t27, so this possibility is impossible.

2. NT18 → NT23 NT57  
   NT57 → 't31' (only choice)  
   NT23 → NT26 NT54  
    NT26 → 't49' | 't23'  
    NT54 → 't33'  

   Hence NT18 would have to generate exactly one of the two three-token sequences  
    t49 t33 t31  or  t23 t33 t31  

   The given string begins t27 t40 t48 … , so neither sequence appears at the start.

Since neither way for NT18 matches the beginning of the string, S cannot derive the string at all, and consequently the grammar does not generate the provided string.

No
